{{Infobox person | name = Carl Ballantine | image = Carl Ballantine 1968.jpg | caption = Ballantine in 1968. | birth_name = Meyer Kessler | birth_date = {{birth date|1917|9|27}} | birth_place = [[Chicago, Illinois]], [[United States|U.S.]] | death_date = {{death date and age|mf=yes|2009|11|3|1917|9|27}} | death_place = [[Hollywood Hills, California]], U.S. | spouse = Ceil Cabot (1955&ndash;2000; her death); 2 daughters | occupation = Actor, magician and comedian | years_active = 1949–2009}}
'''Carl Ballantine''' (September 27, 1917 – November 3, 2009) was an [[United States|American]] [[Magic (illusion)|magician]], [[comedian]] and [[actor]]. Billing himself as "The Great Ballantine", "The Amazing Ballantine" or "Ballantine: The World's Greatest Magician", his [[vaudeville]]-style comedy routine involved transparent or incompetent [[stage magic]] tricks, which tended to flop and go "hilariously awry" to the wisecracking Ballantine's mock chagrin. He has been credited with creating comedy magic and has influenced both comics and magicians.<ref name="mclellan">{{cite news| url=http://www.latimes.com/news/obituaries/la-me-carl-ballantine5-2009nov05,0,162389,full.story| author=Dennis McLellan| title=Carl Ballantine dies at 92; comedy magician was in 'McHale's Navy' cast| newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]| date= November 5, 2009| accessdate=May 6, 2011}}</ref>
==Life and career== Ballantine was born '''Meyer Kessler''' in [[Chicago]], [[Illinois]], the son of Israel Kessler (1883-1930) and Rose Cohen (1890-1973), both Jewish immigrants from [[Borshchiv]], [[Ukraine]] and [[Russian Poland]] (then part of the [[Austrian Empire]] and [[Second Polish Republic]]).<ref>{{cite web | url = http://jri-poland.org | title = Borszczow PSA AGAD Births 1872-98,1901-03 Marriages 1846,55-58,61,62,64,66-1905 Deaths 1877-1902| publisher = jri-poland.org | accessdate=2016-12-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://familysearch.org | title = Israel Kessler and Rose Kessler (Cohen), United States Census, 1930| publisher = archives.gov| accessdate=2016-12-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://familysearch.org | title = Israel Kessler, Illinois, Cook County Deaths| publisher = ilsos.gov| accessdate=2016-12-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://familysearch.org | title = Rose Kessler, Illinois, Cook County Deaths| publisher = ilsos.gov| accessdate=2016-12-18}}</ref> Nicknamed the "Jipper," he was inspired at age 9 by his barber who would do magic tricks with thimbles while cutting his hair. His first job was working as a printer. In the 1930s, Kessler was doing professional straight magic as "Count Marakoff", "Carlton Sharpe", and "Carl Sharp" in Chicago, helping support his family, and later moved to [[New York City]], where he performed in night clubs and on television variety shows. In the early 1940s, he gave up "real magic" when he realized he could not be as good as some of his peers. According to his daughter, “one night, one of his tricks got screwed up, he said something to cover, and the audience laughed. So he started adding more.”<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.jewishjournal.com/arts/page2/jewish_masters_of_magic_materialize_at_skirball_20110425/| date=April 25, 2011| title=Jewish masters of magic materialize at Skirball| author= Edmon J. Rodman|newspaper=[[The Jewish Journal of Greater Los Angeles|Jewish Journal]] | accessdate=May 6, 2011}}</ref> He switched to comedy magic and changed his name to "Carl Ballantine", after he noticed a bottle of [[Ballantine's|Ballantine whisky]] in an advertisement and decided it sounded "show-businessy and classy", and called the magic act "Ballantine, the World's Greatest Magician". He entertained troops during World War Two. He was billed as "The Amazing Mr. Ballantine" when he played the New York Capitol in 1950, and "The Great Ballantine" in ''[[The Ed Sullivan Show]]'' and ''[[The Steve Allen Show]]'' on television in the 1950s and 1960s.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newsfromme.com/archives/2009_11_03.html#017999 |title=Carl Ballantine, R.I.P. |publisher=news from me blog |accessdate=May 6, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100317110200/http://www.newsfromme.com/archives/2009_11_03.html |archivedate=March 17, 2010 |df= }}</ref> He was the first magician to play Las Vegas, appearing on a bill with [[Harry James]], [[Betty Grable]] and [[Sammy Davis Jr.]] at [[El Rancho Vegas]] in 1956.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.thewrap.com/tv/ind-column/obit-actor-carl-ballantine-dies-92-9697| title=Obit: Actor Carl Ballantine Dies at 92| date=November 4, 2009| newspaper=The Wrap news | accessdate=May 6, 2011}}</ref>
[[File:Carl Ballantine McHales Navy 1962.JPG|thumb|left|180px|Ballantine as Lester Gruber in ''McHale's Navy'']] Ballantine was cast in several movies including ''[[McHale's Navy (1964 film)|McHale's Navy]]'' (1964), ''[[Penelope (1966 film)|Penelope]]'' (1966), ''[[Speedway (1968 film)|Speedway]]'' (1968), ''[[The Shakiest Gun in the West]]'' (1968), ''[[The World's Greatest Lover]]'' (1977), ''[[Just You and Me, Kid]]'' (1979), Disney's ''[[The North Avenue Irregulars]]'' (1979) and [[Billy Crystal]]’s directorial debut, ''[[Mr. Saturday Night]]'' (1992), and in numerous television series, including the [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] [[sitcom]] ''[[McHale's Navy]]'' (1962–1966), in which he played Lester Gruber, one of the [[PT boat]] sailors known for his hucksterism and wild schemes. He was a supporting player on the show, working with star [[Ernest Borgnine]], [[Joe Flynn (US actor)|Joe Flynn]] and [[Tim Conway]]. An early television role cast him as Magician “Al Henderson”, working the 53rd precinct Christmas Party for brother-in-law Officer Toody in episode 15 of the 1st season of ''[[Car 54, Where Are You?]]'', first airing December 24, 1961. He also guest starred on ''[[The Partridge Family]]'', ''[[I Dream of Jeannie]]'' as a used car salesman, and on ''[[The Monkees (TV series)|The Monkees]]'' episode called "The Audition" which aired on January 23, 1967. He appeared on ''[[CHiPs]]'' as magician "The Great Marvello." The episode was entitled "Rustling" and aired January 28, 1978. In 1973 he appeared as Dr. Hankim in ''[[The Girl Most Likely to...]]''. His last feature film appearance was in ''Aimee Semple McPherson'', a 2006 [[biopic]] about the female evangelist. Ballantine made his only appearance on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] as Lycus the slave merchant in the 1972 revival of ''[[A Funny Thing Happened on the Way to the Forum]]'' starring [[Phil Silvers]].<ref name="webernyt">{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/10/arts/10ballantine.html?ref=obituaries| author=Bruce Weber| title= Carl Ballantine, Comedian Who Played a Magician, Dies at 92| newspaper=[[The New York Times]]| date= November 10, 2009| accessdate=May 6, 2011}}</ref> He was also a frequent panelist/judge on ''[[The Gong Show]]'', even appearing on the series finale of the NBC daytime version.
In later years he was a recurring voice artist on ''[[Garfield and Friends]]'', usually as Al J. Swindler, a purveyor of shoddy merchandise and goods.{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}}
==Death== Ballantine died on November 3, 2009 at age 92 at his home in [[Hollywood, California]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/afterword/2009/11/carl-ballantines-final-exit.html| title=Comedian-magician Carl Ballantine's final exit| date=November 4, 2009 | author=Dennis McLellan| newspaper=The Los Angeles Times | accessdate=May 6, 2011}}</ref> His remains were cremated.
==Personal== Ballantine's first marriage ended in divorce. In 1955 he married actress Ceil Cabot (born '''Celia Cabrera'''; March 8, 1927 – January 24, 2000),<ref>{{IMDb name|id=0127679|name=Ceil Cabot}}</ref> to whom he remained married until her death in 2000. Their two daughters, Saratoga, an actress,<ref>{{IMDb name|id=0050547|name=Saratoga Ballantine}}</ref> and Molly, an advertising sales executive, are both named after racetracks.<ref>[http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/carl-ballantine-dies-92-90890 "Carl Ballantine dies at 92"], hollywoodreporter.com; accessed June 28, 2015.</ref>
==Awards and honors== He won the [[Academy of Magical Arts]]' (AMA) ''Special Fellowship'' in 1973, ''Performing Fellowship'' in 1984,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.magiccastle.com/ama/awards/index.cfm| title=Awards won by Carl Ballantine| publisher=The Magic Castle| accessdate=May 6, 2011| deadurl=yes| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100917020211/http://www.magiccastle.com/ama/awards/index.cfm| archivedate=September 17, 2010| df=}}</ref> and the "Louie" Award from [[Tannen's Magic Shop|Tannen's Magic]] in 1985.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.insidemagic.com/magicnews/2009/11/09/steve-dacris-tribute-to-carl-ballantine/| newspaper=Inside Magic| title=Steve Dacri’s Tribute to Carl Ballantine| author=Steve Dacri|authorlink=Steve Dacri|date=November 2009|accessdate=May 6, 2011}}</ref> In 2007, he received the 2006 ''Lifetime Achievement Fellowship'' from the Academy of Magical Arts. The award was presented by [[Steve Martin]], who calls Ballantine "the king of bungling magicians" in his memoir ''[[Born Standing Up]]'',<ref>{{cite book| url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NqBNe1RIDHsC&q=ballantine#v=snippet&q=ballantine&f=false|title=Born Standing Up. A comic's life| author=Steve Martin| publisher=Simon and Schuster| year= 2007 | location=New York| isbn= 978-1-4165-5364-9 |page=47}}</ref> and said in an interview: "Carl Ballantine influenced not only myself but a generation of magicians and comedians. His was also the most copied act by a host of amateurs and professionals." According to [[David Copperfield (illusionist)|David Copperfield]], "Carl Ballantine created comedy magic. The combination of magic and comedy had perhaps been done before, but he truly defined it and made it his own."<ref name="mclellan"/>
