{{Infobox company |name = Quicksilver |logo = Quicksilver logo.jpg |type = |foundation = |location_city = |location_country = |location = UK |locations = 200+ |key_people = |area_served = UK |industry = Gambling |products = amusement arcade and gambling machines |services = |operating_income = |revenue = |net_income = |num_employees = |parent = [[Novomatic]] }}
[[File:Old and New - geograph.org.uk - 1348402.jpg|thumb|A Quicksilver branch in Halifax, England, in 2009 with the old branding.]] [[File:Quicksilver, Wood Green.jpg|thumb|A Quicksilver branch in Wood Green, London.]] '''Quicksilver''' is a British amusement arcade and gambling machine company. It is the UK's largest slot gambling machine operator, with over 200 high street outlets and about 10,000 gambling machines.<ref name="RecruitmentRevoltuion">{{cite web|title=Talarius Case Study|url=https://www.recruitmentrevolution.com/case-studies/talarius|website=RecruitmentRevolution|accessdate=8 July 2016}}</ref> Quicksilver describes itself as the "largest amusement business in the UK".<ref name=Quicksilver />
==Operations== In conjunction with their parent company, Talarius, they operate three high street brands across the UK, Quicksilver, Silvers and Winners, including eight at motorway service areas.<ref name=Quicksilver>{{cite web|title=Quicksilver|url=http://stores.quicksilver.co.uk/|website=Quicksilver|accessdate=24 April 2015}}</ref>
In 2007, the profitability of the firm was hit when the British government introduced a new taxation regime for gambling and a [[Smoking in the United Kingdom|smoking ban]] on commercial premises but the company has since recovered.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bmmagazine.co.uk/entrepreneur-interviews/getting-to-know-you/getting-to-know-you-peter-harvey-ceo-talarius/|title=Getting To Know You: Peter Harvey, CEO, Talarius|date=6 May 2015|publisher=}}</ref>
Since 2012, Quicksilver have run the arcades at all [[Extra (service areas)|Extra motorway service stations]] in the UK, and from 2013, the arcade at the Folkestone service station on the M20.<ref name="MSO">{{cite web|title=Quicksilver|url=http://motorwayservicesonline.co.uk/Quicksilver|website=Motorway Services Online|accessdate=8 July 2016}}</ref>
In 2013, Talarius and Quicksilver left the trade body BACTA after becoming dissatisfied with the direction it was taking but rejoined in 2014 following the appointment of John White as chief executive.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbcnews.co.uk/retail/2014/07/29/talarius-rejoins-bacta/|title=Talarius rejoins BACTA|publisher=}}</ref>
In September 2015, [[Playtech]] reached a deal to provide its software to 92 of Talarius' Quicksilver-branded UK high street "adult gaming centres" (AGCs).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.igamingbusiness.com/news/playtech-provide-retail-software-talarius|title=Playtech to provide retail software to Talarius|date=4 September 2015|publisher=}}</ref> In July 2016, [[Gamestec]] a subsidiary of [[Novomatic]], extended their logistics contract to provide "extensive network and infrastructure capacity" for a third year to over 180 Quicksilver outlets.<ref>[http://www.gamestec.co.uk/en/gamestec/news-events/talarius-and-gamestec-agree-extension-on-logistics-contract Talarius and Gamestec agree extension on logistics contract.] Gamestec, 3 March 2014. Retrieved 5 September 2016.</ref>
==Ownership== Quicksilver is part of Talarius, which was owned by the Australian [[Tatts Group]] from 2008 until it was sold to Austrian company [[Novomatic]] in June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.intergameonline.com/coin-op/news/16157/novomatic-buys-talarius|title=Novomatic buys Talarius - News - Coin-op - InterGame|publisher=}}</ref>
